foliation.note: Numbering in ink at top centre of recto of each leaf.

Numbering in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the first leaf of each quire by M.R. James. James divides the book into three parts: 1-56v (actually two booklets) and the remainder. James mistook the shape of quire 9 and misfoliated some later portions of the manuscript, which may have hindered his recognition procedures; his third part consists of the binding materials at the end, separate from the final text quire. The foliation provided on CUDL has been added in pencil since the digitisation.

collation.p:
The manuscript is composed of varying formats.
Quire 18-4 (ff. 1-4: leaves 3-6 missing)
Quire 28 (ff. 5-12)
Quire 38 (ff. 13-20)
Quire 48 (ff. 21-28)
Quire 58 (ff. 29-36)
Quire 68 (ff. 37-44)
Quire 712 (ff. 45-56)
Quire 86 (ff. 57-62)
Quire 98 (ff. 63-70)
Quire 1012 (ff. 71-82)
Quire 1114 (ff. 83-94b)
Quire 1212-1 (ff. 95-105: leaf 12 missing)
Quire 1312 (ff. 106-117)
Quire 1412 (ff. 118-129)

p.signatures: Medieval signatures on first recto of each quire. Modern signatures probably by M.R. James.

layout.seg: Single columns only, ruled in leadpoint, frame only, 36-47 lines to the page.

handNote.p: Anglicana, probably three hands, quires 1-4 and probably 12-14, 5-9, and 10-11, plus a lost quire; the filler-items are in similar hands but not assignable.

decoNote.p: Paragraph marks and underlining in red.

additions.note: The front flyleaf and the last at the rear (raised pastedown) from a theological (?) discussion, anglicana (13th century). The rear flyleaf is preceded by three leaves (ff. 132r-134v) with notes (15th century). At the head of the rear flyleaf, in contemporary Middle English, 'Schak ye tayl and mak hit wele quod hending in may', certainly proverbial and octosyllabic verse, but not from the collection customarily ascribed to Hending (conceivably with reference to the owner 'Thomas Wele'?).

binding.p: Medieval, brown calfskin over wooden boards, a scar from a strap-seating at the centre of the upper board.

history.provenance: Certainly a communal production by associated hands, and certainly members of the same religious group. Cf. the invocations at the openings of individual stints: f. 29 (scribe 2), 'Assit principio sancta Maria mea'; f. 71 (scribe 3), 'Maria thomas katerina'; f. 95 (i.e. real 97, scribe 1) 'Assit principio sancta Maria mea katerina'.
A not especially legible inscription, 15th century (fol. 37, in the outer margin), ? 'Ihon de Ihorn'; no plausible candidate appears in either BRUO or BRUC.

'Thomas Wele', mid-15th century, (f. 19v and 20r, in the upper margins): probably to be associated with a man of the name, who was vicar of St Cyriac's, Swaffham Prior (Cambs.), 1458x1468 (Emden, BRUC 625).

Hanna suggests that the manuscript is very likely from a Dominican house, and although there are a number of East Midland candidates, the most proximate at Thetford and Northampton, most probably from that in Cambridge.
history.acquisition: James suggests that the volume was probably donated in the early 1630s by Francis Tyndall Tyndall, Francis, who gave several manuscripts to the library.
